  "prompt": "What's the difference between slugs and snails, besides the shell?",
  "response": "While both slugs and snails belong to the class Gastropoda, there are several differences between them besides the presence of a shell:\n\n1. **Shell**: The most obvious difference is that snails have a prominent external spiral shell that they can retract into for protection, whereas slugs do not have such a shell. Slugs might have an internal vestigial shell or none at all.\n\n2. **Body Structure**: Due to the lack of a shell, slugs have a more flexible and elongated body, allowing them to maneuver through narrower spaces compared to snails.\n\n3. **Habitat**: Slugs are generally more adapted to living in moist environments where the absence of a shell makes movement easier and reduces the risk of dehydration. Snails, in contrast, can be found in a wider range of habitats due to their protective shell.\n\n4. **Behavior**: Slugs tend to be more active in damp and dark conditions, often coming out at night to avoid drying out. Snails may be more visible during the day but also prefer moist conditions.\n\n5. **Moisture Dependency**: Slugs are more sensitive to drying out than snails because the shell provides snails with protection against desiccation.\n\n6. **Reproduction**: Although both slugs and snails are hermaphrodites, the specifics of their reproductive processes and mating behaviors can differ.\n\nIn summary, while the shell is a primary distinguishing factor, differences in body structure, habitat preference, behavior, and moisture dependency also set them apart.",
